doctype html
html(lang="en")
  head
    script(src="http://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.11.1/jquery.min.js", type="text/javascript")
    script(data-guidedog-path='/css/app.css', data-logo-path='https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/35838577/logo.jpg', src='/dist/guidedog.min.js', type='text/javascript')
    link(rel='stylesheet', type='text/css', href='/css/app.css')
  body
    p Guidedog requires a server to work, you cannot view HTML files directly in your file system. This means you want the URL to read something like http://mysite.com or //http://localhost:3000/ and NOT file:///Users/local/path/to/guidedog/example.html. Luckily, Guidedog comes with a simple Node server to get you started. To start the server, simply navigate to the root Guidedog folder in Terminal, and run `gulp`.
    p Note - You'll have to install Node in order to start the server.
    script.
      $(document).on('guidedogReady', function() {
        $('head').append('<script type="text/javascript" src="/js/app.min.js" />')
      });
